@RohitSurwase commented on [Mon Oct 15 2018](https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/23086#issuecomment-429745922)

Hey! The issue resolved. 
I was importing Android Studio settings from the previous version every time. Just tried deleting and creating fresh new settings and it worked.
Thanks for helping.

comment_data.body: Not sure there is anything that needs to/can be done.

Thanks for the feedback!

I'm not sure the stale settings issue is likely to hit other folks (or how anomalous it was)... 

Optimistically closing but @stevemessick do feel free to re-open if you have any insights.

Just wanted to chime in here: @filiph and I are running a workshop today and one of our attendees ran into this same problem: No wizard appeared or options to create a new flutter project. 

Installing / reinstalling the Flutter and Dart plugins didn't work, and deleting their settings wasn't a viable option since they use Android Studio as their primary IDE for work projects.

Creating a project from the command line and using Android Studio to open the project worked fine.

We looked at the IntelliJ logs and didn't see any errors related to Flutter. Overall, we might not be able to stay in touch with this person, but wanted to let you know it was happening for others users as well, maybe to keep an eye on it if others report similar issues.

Though you are not looking for a temporary solution here are the steps for it-
(For anyone looking for a quick fix)

Cause- We are importing settings from the previous version of Android Studio as a general practice.

Solution-
Step 1: Remove Flutter and Dart plugin from Studio.
Step 2: In the command line
`flutter channel master` (switch to master branch)
`flutter doctor` (get updates from master branch)

Step 3: Close AS and delete all previous settings folders (AndroidStudio3.1, AndroidStudio3.2 ...) Now, start AS with fresh new settings.

Step 4: Install Dart plugin first, restart AS. Install Flutter Plugin, restart AS.
And your Android Studio is ready for Flutter. :)

It sounds like there may be some metadata in AS which is either preventing us from displaying the Flutter wizard contribution, or which we're keying off to see if we should display the wizard contribution.

> No wizard appeared or options to create a new flutter project

Not clear what this means. If "no wizard appeared" when you did something to cause a wizard to appear, what was it that you did?

If "options to create" were not present then did you do something that should have invoked the wizard?

By "wizard" are we talking about the New Project Wizard that is used to create Flutter projects in Android Studio?

There are two ways to invoke the New Project Wizard in Android Studio. If no project window is open the Welcome Screen has as its second option "Start a new Flutter project". Was that present or absent? The other option is from the main menu: File > New > New Flutter Project. Was that present or absent?
@stevemessick I request you go through the previous comments because the answers that you are looking for are already there.

Hi @stevemessick -- I'll try to answer each question!

  > By "wizard" are we talking about the New Project Wizard that is used to create Flutter projects in Android Studio?

Exactly. The Wizard you get by clicking on "Start a new Flutter Project" from the Welcome screen.
 
  > Not clear what this means. If "no wizard appeared" when you did something to cause a wizard to appear, what was it that you did? 

User had Android studio installed and working for normal android projects. They install Flutter, Flutter Plugin, and Dart Plugin. On the "Welcome" screen, there is no option to "Start a new flutter project" nor is the "New Flutter Project" available in the File > New menu. There was just no way to create a Flutter project from Android Studio.
 
  > If "options to create" were not present then did you do something that should have invoked the wizard?

It appears the solution was to wipe out the Android Studio preferences directory and start fresh. That wasn't a viable option for this person since they had Android Studio properly configured for their day-to-day Android work, so we never got the "New Project Wizard" working and had to create the app via the command line.

Overall, it was just a bit of a rough first experience for a new Flutter user, and it might be worth investigating.
The attendee's version was the same as my own, a stable 3.2.1.

Without additional information we're unfortunately not sure how to resolve this issue. We're going to close this bug for now, but please don't hesitate to comment on the bug if you have any more information for us; we're happy to reopen. Thanks for your contribution!
